snippet.textDisplay:
Maybe I'm not the normal audience for this type of machine but I don't think I'd install it in a data center or server room. I don't need to access it remotely. Either I'd:


1: Install it in a rack in my studio with my Focusrite Scarlett 18i20 and other fancy AV gear. That way I could keep my video and audio rendering stuff better organized and off my desk, which would have room for the ultrawide monitors, control surfaces, etc. This isn't perfect since I may need access to a SAN for handling large video files.


2: Put it it in the biggest Gator I could find along with the Scarlett, a few amps, and a power supply. I'd haul it to my gigs and use it for performances. Plug it directly into a projector and PA system. This is nearly a concert tour-ready system for projection mapping, ambisonics, EDM, etc. It's a little bit overkill but it depends on how far down the rabbit hole you want to go and how much money you have to throw at your performance kit. Average guy like yours truly doesn't need it but I could imagine someone like Bjork, Tiesto, NiN, Ark Patrol, Imogen Heap, or Big Wild making use of this configuration or even more. This would allow for seriously low latency live signal processing from multiple audio inputs and, with the right video card, video signals as well. Iannis Xenakis' ghost is having wet dreams about this setup.


I'm currently building a rig like that now. Just without a Mac...and more like a 6U where the server style workstation is 2U. But I'd rather have MacOS instead of Windows. That monster is WAY more expensive than what I've got spec'd.

snippet.textDisplay: Yeah, this is huge for the video/audio production folks. Rackmounts for studios is a really nice plus, but for those in the production world, this is really a huge plus. Touring with computers is a huge problem and often requires massively custom solutions. This is one of the first times you can easily ship a high powered mac out of the box for live productions, either as a recording PC, live streaming PC, video/projections setup, or a cue machine. Production companies with the budgets that need this kind of power will eat up that markup to easily be able to include this in a rack at front of house.

snippet.textDisplay: I think the other ENORMOUS use case for this machine is Mac OS virtualization. Every software company that develops software for Macs wants to be able run automated integration testing on Mac OS, and running these illegally or on a pile of Mac minis stacked in a corner of the office is just not a realistic option at scale. There are even entire companies dedicated to providing Mac VMs in the cloud, and you can best bet they will be buying enormous numbers of these, especially with the RAM and CPU configs that are available. Apple isn’t competing against a Dell server here, they’re competing against framing up a bunch of Mac Minis or trashcans in some janky racking system with no hardware options more or less.

In certain applications, these builds can take a long time, optimize for a different architecture, run tests, etc. I remember in my company we used to have a data center with Linux racks for android builds and then some weird trashcan rig mac pro. It would be so much better if we had a rack like this. It is not high availability, so it doesn't need a backup power supply and etc.

snippet.textDisplay:
As someone that has worked in a datacenter, the quietness of a Mac Pro would be very much appreciated. Unfortunately when the CTO or CIO asks to spend 15% more for hearing safety concerns at the board meeting, the CFO is going to respond by suggesting earplugs.


And i have another 2 potential use cases. If you have one of those hipster open concept offices with a bunch of people working around the same table, stacking a bunch of Rac Pros in the center makes a much cleaner work place than having a Mac Pro in every gap. Or if you operate like me with your workstation, NAS, and DMZ server all in the same home office, rack mounting them along with a switch and UPS makes a lot of sense.

snippet.textDisplay: Not just to guard against PSU failure.  It's not unusual, in data centers focused on high availability, to have two PDUs (power strips) in each rack.  Each PDU will connect to a separate UPS and generator, so that if something goes wrong (like a generator failing to start in an emergency), each server will still have half of its power supplies powered.
